{Black's queenside expansion ***After my Gruenfeld series, this is the start
of a new string of articles, strategic and theoretical ones, dedicated to the
Benoni defense. Unlike in the Gruenfeld, there is not such a wide variety of
structures in the Benoni. It mainly depends on such issues as whether White
consolidates his e4-pawn with f2-f3, or prepares to launch it forward with
f2-f4 etc. But the main issue is the same: White has a mobile majority in the
center, while Black has the same on the queenside. ***Obviously, White's most
daring dream is carrying out a queenside expansion, involving ...b7-b5
followed, according to the circumstances, by ...c5-c4 or ...b5-b4. Here is an
example in which this plan was consequently carried out:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Bf4
a6 11. a4 {[#]} b6 $5 {A relatively rare move. Black prevents a4-a5, a typical
way of disrupting the queenside structure flexibility.} 12. Re1 Nh5 13. Bg5 Qc7
14. e4 Nd7 15. Rc1 h6 16. Bd2 Qb8 17. Bf1 {Returning to the initial diagonal
in order to slow down ...b6-b5.} Ra7 18. b3 Nf8 19. h3 Rae7 20. Qc2 g5 $5 {
Black plays for space on both wings. The last move clears the g6-square for
the knight.} 21. Kg2 Ng6 22. Bd3 Nf6 23. Rh1 Qb7 24. Rce1 Bd7 {Black has
reached a perfect regrouping using the communication between the opposite
wings along the 7th and 8th ranks and ...b6-b5 cannot be stopped anymore.} 25.
Bc1 b5 26. axb5 axb5 27. Bb2 {[#]After achieving the first major queenside
success, Black needs a plan for making further progress. Gashimov found an
interesting tactical idea involving both wings.} c4 $1 ({The same combination
as in the game does not work as well as in the game without the prior pawn
sacrifice:} 27... Bxh3+ 28. Rxh3 g4 29. Rhh1 gxf3+ 30. Kxf3 c4 31. bxc4 bxc4
32. Bf1 Ne5+ 33. Kg2 Nd3 34. Bxd3 cxd3 35. Qd2 $15 {and White still holds.})
28. bxc4 bxc4 29. Bxc4 $6 ({This adds wood on the fire as it exposes White
along the c-file and the bishop as well,} 29. Bf1 $5 $15 {was more cautious.})
{[#]} 29... Bxh3+ $1 {Everything is prepared now for this combination.} 30. Kg1
({With the bishop on c4} 30. Rxh3 {loses to} g4 31. Rhh1 $6 gxf3+ 32. Kxf3 $2
Ne5+) (30. Kxh3 {is no better:} g4+ 31. Kh2 gxf3 {with a decisive attack.})
30... Rc8 {The pin along the c-file and the pressure on c3 are very annoying
for White.} 31. Ba2 $2 ({This loses by force, but} 31. Nd2 {is not rosy either:
} Ne5 32. Be2 Bg4 33. Kg2 Bxe2 34. Rxe2 Qa6 $17 {with strong initiative on
light squares.}) 31... Nxe4 32. Rxh3 Nxc3 33. Rxe7 Nxe7 34. Bxc3 Rxc3 35. Qe4
g4 {Not the only winning move. Black deflects the queen from the defense of
the b1-square in order to trap the bishop.} 36. Qxg4 Qa6 0-1

