{White's pressure along the f1-a6 diagonal sometimes requires from Black
changing the move order when advancing his queenside pawns. More specifically,
...c5-c4 is a typical way of preparing ...b5. Here is a typical example
involving some tactical nuances:} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 c5 5. d5
d6 6. e4 O-O 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. Nd2 a6 11. a4 b6 12. Qc2
Nbd7 13. f4 Rb8 14. Rb1 {[#]With the actual piece placement Black cannot
increase his control over b5. The maneuver ...Ne8-c7 would require too much
time as the e8-square is not available yet, allowing White to take over the
initiative with either e4-e5 or b2-b4. But the Benoni virtuoso Velimirovic
found a very effective way of continuing his queenside plan.} c4 $1 15. Kh1 {
This neutral move does not prevent Black's plan in any way, but there was no
effective antidote available:} (15. Nxc4 {weakens the defense of e4, causing
White stability problems after} Nc5 16. e5 $5 (16. Bf3 b5 17. Nd2 b4 18. Ne2 a5
$17 {leaves White with too many passive pieces.}) 16... Bf5 17. Qd1 dxe5 18.
Ra1 (18. fxe5 Nxd5 $1) 18... exf4 19. Bxf4 Nfe4 20. Bxb8 Qxb8 21. Nxe4 Rxe4 $15
{Black will soon win the d5-pawn with overwhelming compensation for the
exchange.}) (15. Bxc4 {leaves the g4-square undefended allowing} Ng4 $1 16. Nf3
b5 $1 {As always, combining threats on both wings is very effective.} 17. axb5
axb5 18. Bd3 b4 19. Na4 Qa5 {planning...Ba6} 20. h3 Qa7+ 21. Kh1 Ba6 $1 22.
Bxa6 (22. hxg4 b3 23. Qe2 Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Qxa4 $17 {wins the e4-pawn soon.})
22... Qxa6 23. Bd2 Ngf6 24. Rfe1 Rbc8 $17 {followed by ...Nxe4 with
overwhelming activity.}) (15. b4 {does not work out too well either:} cxb3 16.
Rxb3 Nc5 17. Rb4 Bd7 $36 {followed by ...b6-b5 soon.}) 15... b5 $17 {[#]With
devastating initiative already.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. b4 cxb3 18. Rxb3 b4 19. Nb5
Nc5 20. Rxb4 Nxd5 21. exd5 Rxe2 22. Qc4 Re7 23. Nxd6 Ba6 24. Nb5 Qb6 25. d6
Reb7 26. Ba3 Ne6 27. Rfb1 Qf2 28. Ne4 Qxf4 29. Bc1 Qf5 30. Ng3 Qf2 31. Nf1 Bd4
0-1

