{Sometimes fighting for queenside space implies parting with the pride of
Black's position, his g7-bishop. This can be successful only if the queenside
events are intense enough to keep White busy without allowing him starting a
kingside attack. Here is such an example:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3
d6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. Nf3 e6 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. Nd2 Na6 11. f3
Nc7 12. a4 b6 13. Nc4 Ba6 14. Rb1 {White not only speeds up his queenside play
with respect to the previous game but also prepares to defend the c3-knight
with his bishop, instead of setting up the sterile pin of the f6-knight.} Bxc4
15. Bxc4 Nd7 16. Bd2 a6 17. b4 cxb4 18. Rxb4 Qe7 19. Kh1 Rec8 20. Qe2 {[#]
White has considerable space advantage and an apparently solid position. If
allowed completing his regrouping with Rfb1 his advantage would be
indisputable but Black can strike first.} b5 $1 21. axb5 Bxc3 $1 22. Bxc3 axb5
{Suddenly it is not easy finding a good square for the bishop. The point is
that Black's apparently passive knights have a lot of hidden energy.} 23. Ba2 {
The best move.} ({The main alternative is} 23. Bd3 Nxd5 24. exd5 Qxe2 25. Bxe2
Rxc3 $15 {offering Black a pleasant ending with a dominating knight over the
bishop.}) (23. Bxb5 $2 Nxb5 $19 {leaves the c3-bishop hanging.}) (23. Bb3 Na6
$19 {does the same.}) 23... Na6 {The point of Black's previous play. Even
though his bishop occupies the attacking diagonal, White is not in time to
create any threats.} 24. Rb3 Nac5 {[#]} 25. Rxb5 $6 {Too ambitious.} ({White
should have accepted a draw by repetition with} 25. Rb4 Na6 $11) 25... Nxe4 $1
{White must have thought that this is placing the knight under a pin, without
noticing the threat ...Ng3!+. This means he has no time saving his c3-bishop
from an exchange in order to keep attacking chances.} 26. fxe4 (26. Bc4 {
looks as the lesser evil:} Ng3+ 27. hxg3 Qxe2 28. Bxe2 Rxc3 $15) 26... Rxc3 $17
{Black's central structure is awful and his bishop does not make his position
better.} 27. Rb7 Qe8 28. Qb5 Nc5 (28... Ne5 $5 $17) 29. Qxe8+ Rxe8 30. Rbxf7
Nxe4 31. Ra7 Rec8 32. Rb7 Rc2 33. Ra7 Rb2 34. Re1 Nf2+ 35. Kg1 Nd3 36. Rf1 Rcc2
0-1

