{[#]White needs playing Rfb1 or Rc1 for consolidating and eventually winning
the b5-pawn. However, he is temporarily hanging. Is there a way Black could
put all his pieces to work (including the h5-knight) in order to get
counterplay?} 20... Rec8 $6 {This is too neutral to bother White.} (20... Qc5
$1 {was the right move, causing White problems on dark squares:} 21. Rfb1 (21.
Qb3 {is somewhat similar:} Nxg3 $1 22. fxg3 Rxe3 23. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Kh2 Qxc3 {
with great compensation for the exchange.}) 21... Nxg3 $1 22. fxg3 (22. Rxb5 {
loses to the intermediate} Ne2+ $1 23. Kf1 Nxc3 24. Rxc5 Rxb1+ 25. Be1 Nxc5 $19
{with decisive material advantage and a continuing attack.}) 22... Rxe3 23.
Bxe3 (23. Kh2 $2 Rxc3 24. Bxc3 Bxc3 $17 {followed by ...b5-b4 leaves White
very passive.}) 23... Qxe3+ 24. Kh2 Qxc3 ({Better than} 24... Bxc3 25. R1b3 Rc8
26. Re4) 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rxb5 Rd8 $5 $44 {Black temporarily defends the
knight, preparing ...Kg7 and eventually ...Ne5 after some more preparing, so
as not to allow the rook exchange too soon. Generally, Black's position is a
perfect fortress.}) 21. Rc1 Ne5 22. Qb1 Nc4 23. Be1 $16 {with perfect white
coordination. With the h5-knight far from the important areas, the b5-pawn is
doomed.} 1-0

