1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
O-O 9. O-O {In many openings where Black refrains from early fight for the
center (for instance in the King's Indian or the Sicilian Najdorf or
Scheveningen), White has at his disposal the so-called classical system. As in
the current position, he does not try refuting Black's opening but develops
normally (Nf3, Be2 are typical harmonious moves) counting on that his space
advantage should tell in the middlegame struggle. Even though Black seems
enjoying some early freedom, he should plan his actions with care and accuracy
in order to avoid being left in a passive position.} a6 10. a4 Bg4 {With the
given move order this is the most reliable system. In the Benoni there
frequently is a conflict between the minor pieces (with the exception of the
g7-bishop, which has its own play). Mainly there are competing for the
d7-square, causing some problems of coordination and development. This issue
is also typical for the Breyer Ruy Lopez or the lines with a blocked center in
the King's Indian. Therefore, if Black can exchange his bishop he should not
refrain from it, as this greatly solves his problems of space. As a
consequence of the exchange Black's dream plan is ...c5-c4 followed by the
invasion of the d3-square with a knight.} 11. Nd2 {Since occupying the
c4-square with a knight is vital for White, exchanging bishops this way is
logical. But the main problem is that the last move causes some delay in
development, allowing Black organizing his play against the e4-pawn.} (11. h3
Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {not only loses time with respect to Line 2 (actually White may
for several reasons play h2-h3 later) but more importantly allows Black
obtaining the perfect regrouping:} Nbd7 13. Bf4 Qc7 $1 {The queen stands best
on this square, as it sustains ...c5-c4 and leaves the e-file available to the
rook, for putting pressure on e4. Compare with Line 2 where the queen has to
go to e7. Once the reader has examined the material in Line 2, this position
will certainly be easier to play, so I just include here a classical example:}
14. a5 {Anticipating ...c5-c4.} Rfe8 15. Qc2 c4 16. Ra4 Ne5 17. Bxe5 (17. Be2
Nfd7 {/\...Nc5.}) 17... Rxe5 18. Nb1 {White has regrouped in such a way as to
win the c4-pawn but Black's pressure in the center proves just as strong.} Rae8
19. Na3 Nxe4 20. Rxc4 Qe7 21. Rc7 Qd8 22. Rxb7 {White has temporarily won a
pawn, but Black's coordination is by far superior.} Ng5 23. Bg4 (23. Bd1 Qxa5
$15) 23... h5 24. Bd7 Nf3+ 25. gxf3 Qg5+ 26. Bg4 (26. Kh1 Re1 $19) (26. Kh2
Qf4+ 27. Kg2 Rg5+ $19) 26... hxg4 27. fxg4 Re1 (27... Qf4 $5 $15) 28. Qc4 Qd2 {
and White reached a draw not without a good share of struggling in Portisch, L
(2620)-Kasparov,G (2630) Tilburg 1981 (½-½, 41)}) (11. Bg5 {is slightly more
consistent but if compared with the main line the bishop does not put
immediate pressure on d6, allowing Black certain freedom of action. Mainly, he
can develop his queen to c7 or a5.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Re8 $5 (12... Nbd7 13. Be2 {
followed by f3.}) 13. Qc2 Nbd7 14. Be2 {Black has scored reasonably well from
this position. Moves such as ...Qc7, and ...Rc8 have been tried, but the
resolute} c4 $5 $146 {is also entirely possible.} 15. Bxc4 Rc8 16. Bd3 (16. Be2
h6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Bf3 h5 19. g3 Nd7 $44 {/\...Nc5}) (16. Qe2 Qb6 {/\...Qb4})
16... Nc5 17. f3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qb6+ 19. Rf2 Nd7 20. Be3 Ne5 21. Qd2 Qb4 22. Nd1
Qxd2 23. Rxd2 f5 24. exf5 gxf5 $44 {Black's superior activity doubtlessly
compensates for the pawn.}) 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nbd7 13. Nc4 (13. a5 Qe7 14.
Nc4 Ne5 15. Ne3 Ned7 16. Nc4 (16. f3 Nh5 17. Nc4 Bd4+ 18. Kh1 Ne5 $132) 16...
Ne5 17. Nb6 {transposes below}) 13... Nb6 {Black should not tolerate the enemy
knight on c4 any single minute.} 14. Ne3 (14. Na3 Re8 {gains a tempo by
threatening ...Nxd5.} 15. Qc2 Nfd7 16. a5 Nc8 17. Nc4 Ne5 18. Ne3 b5 19. axb6
Nxb6 $11 {/\...c4.}) (14. Nxb6 {gains time for developing but frees Black's
play.} Qxb6 15. a5 Qc7 16. Bd2 {[%cal Yb2b4,Gc3a4,Ga4b6] Planning b2-b4 and/or
Na4-b6.} (16. Bf4 Rae8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Yf7f5] Yudasin}) 16... Rae8 $1 {Keeping
the possibility of ...f7-f5.} (16... Rfe8 17. f3 Nd7 18. Qd1 c4 19. Be3 Nc5 20.
Bxc5 Qxc5+ 21. Kh1 b5 22. axb6 Qxb6 $15 {Mohandesi,S-Kurniawan,B/Erevan 1996/
EXT 97 (0-1, 34)}) 17. Rfe1 $1 Nd7 (17... Nxe4 $6 18. Nxe4 f5 19. Nf6+ $1 Bxf6
20. Qxe8 Rxe8 21. Rxe8+ Kf7 22. Rae1 $13 {[%cal Gd2h6] Yudasin}) 18. f4 $1 {
Otherwise black would play f5,and than c4 and Ne5-d3. (Yudasin)} f5 $1 19. Qc4
$1 (19. e5 $2 dxe5 20. Qc4 Qd6 {Yudasin}) 19... Bd4+ $1 (19... fxe4 20. Nxe4 $1
Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 $44 {[%cal Gc4b3,Ge4g5,Gd2c3] /\ Ng5, Bc3, Qb3.
Yudasin}) 20. Kh1 Nf6 (20... fxe4 $2 21. Nxe4 Bxb2 22. Rab1 $36 {Yudasin}) 21.
exf5 (21. e5 $2 dxe5 22. fxe5 Rxe5 23. Rxe5 Qxe5 24. Re1 Qd6 25. Re6 Qd7 $17 {
Yudasin}) 21... gxf5 22. Re6 $1 {Otherwise black takes on-c3 and enters the N
to-e4. (Yudasin)} (22. Qd3 Ng4) 22... Rxe6 $1 23. dxe6 Re8 24. Nd5 $2 (24. Re1
b5 25. axb6 Qxb6 $13) 24... Qc6 $1 25. Nxf6+ $8 Bxf6 $17 {Rapoport,E (2262)
-Yudasin,L (2549) Beersheba 1999 (0-1, 41)}) (14. e5 {does not offer anything
positive as White is not completely developed:} dxe5 15. Nxb6 Qxb6 16. Qxe5
Rfe8 17. Qf4 (17. Qg3 Ne4 18. Nxe4 Rxe4 $15 {><d5, b2, d4.}) 17... Qb4 $15)
14... Qe7 15. a5 Nbd7 16. Nc4 Ne5 17. Nb6 Rae8 {Planning ...Nfd7 followed by ..
.f7-f5.} 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bh4 g5 20. Bg3 Nfd7 21. f4 (21. Nxd7 Nxd7 22. Qc2 h5 $5
$132) 21... gxf4 22. Rxf4 Ng6 $132 23. Nxd7 $2 (23. Rf5 Nxb6 24. axb6 Qd8 25.
Na4 Ne7 26. Rf3 f5 $132) 23... Nxf4 24. Qg4 f5 25. Qxf4 Qxd7 $19 {Harikrishna,
P (2504)-Bu,X (2558) Lausanne 2001 (½-½, 38)} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
