1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2
O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Bg4 11. Bf4 $1 {Doubtlessly the most challenging move.}
Bxf3 $1 {Practice has proven this being Black's most reliable plan, even
though it basically means throwing a tempo away. With the White's queen's
bishop already developed allowing Nd2 is likely to cause problems.} ({The old
main line goes} 11... Re8 12. Nd2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Nh5 14. Be3 Nd7 15. g4 Nhf6 16.
f3 $14 {and Black finds it difficult to get counterplay.}) 12. Bxf3 Qe7 {
Preparing ...Nbd7.} ({Black has to deviate from the optimal regrouping as} 
12... Qc7 {allows} 13. e5 dxe5 14. d6 {retrieving the pawn with space
advantage and two active bishops.}) (12... Re8 13. Re1 Qc7 14. e5 dxe5 15. d6 {
is similar.}) {This is a very popular tabiya in which Black has scored very
well. But I have discovered that in many games White hesitated at the crucial
moment, meaning that objectively are not entirely clear. The positive aspect
is that from a practical point of view Black's play is easier. As a general
observation, I got the feeling that Black should carry out his main plan 
(based as always on ...c5-c4) as quickly as possible. Playing neutral
"generally useful" moves may offer White time for regrouping and consolidating
his space advantage.} 13. Qd2 {The most natural developing move.} (13. Qb3 {
can safely be answered with} Nbd7 {The queen will soon be exposed on b3.} 14.
Rfe1 {Hansen, C-Tisdall,J Gausdal 1987 (0-1, 22)} (14. Qxb7 Rfb8 15. Qc6 Ne8
16. a5 (16. Bg4 Ne5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. f4 Bd4+ 19. Kh1 Qd8 20. e5 f5 $5 21. exf6
Nxf6 22. Be6+ Kh8 23. a5 Rxb2 $17 {Pilar Miloslav-Meduna Eduard,
Czechoslovakia 1988}) 16... Ne5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Rfd1 Ra7 19. Ra2 Nc7 20. Qa4
Rb4 21. Qc2 Rab7 22. Rf1 Nb5 23. Be2 Nd4 24. Qd2 c4 $44 {Hamilton,D-Marin,M
World Chess Network 2001}) (14. a5 Rab8 15. Qc2 (15. Na4 Ne5 {exchanges the
f3-bishop immediately solving Black's space problems as the e4-pawn is hanging.
}) 15... Ne8 16. Rfe1 Nc7 17. Be2 b5 18. axb6 Rxb6 19. Ra2 Rfb8 20. Bd2 Bd4 {
Lautier,J (2632)-Topalov,V (2702) Monte Carlo 2000 (½-½, 65)}) 14... Ne5 15.
Be2 Nh5 $5 16. Bxh5 gxh5 17. Qc2 h4 18. h3 c4 {/\...Nd3} 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Nd1
b5 21. Ne3 Qg5 22. Ng4 (22. Nf5 Kh8) 22... Bf4 $132) (13. Re1 Nbd7 {has
independent value only if White refrains from the early queen development.} 14.
a5 {Aticipating ...c5-c4 but offering Black an alternative.} Rab8 $5 {The same
pshylosophy as explained above. Black immediately starts concrete action along
his new main plan.} 15. Qc2 (15. Na4 Ne5 $1 {><Pe4} 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Nb6 (17.
Rb1 Nd7 18. b4 Qd4 19. Qe2 cxb4 20. Red1 Qf6 21. Bg4 b5 22. axb6 Nxb6 23. Rxb4
Nxa4 24. Rxa4 {½-½ Browne, W-Gurevich, D/USA (ch) 1985 One year later D.
Gurevich decided to play on:} Rb2 25. Qf1 Ra8 26. Rda1 Qf4 27. Bh3 Bc3 28. Rd1
Bb4 $17 {Rao,V-Gurevich, D Midwest Masters Inv. 1986}) 17... Rfe8 18. Nc4 Qe7
19. e5 dxe5 20. Rxe5 Qd7 {Black will soon transfer his knight to d6 with
complete equality.} 21. d6 $2 Rxe5 22. Nxe5 Qe6 $17 {leaves White vulnerable
in the center.}) (15. Be2 b5 $146 ({Once again neutral moves play into White's
hands.} 15... h5 16. Qd2 Rfe8 17. h3 b5 18. axb6 Rxb6 19. Bxa6 Reb8 20. Ra2 {
and Black still needs proving his compensation for the pawn, Chatalbashev, B 
(2543)-Izoria, Z (2573) Antalya 2004 (½-½, 37)}) 16. axb6 Rxb6 17. Qc2 Ra8
18. Bg5 h6 19. Bd2 Ne8 20. Ra2 Nc7 21. f4 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 Nf6 23. Bf3 Rab8 24. Nd1
h5 $13 {Black is perfectly regrouped and has the same kind of activity as in
the aforementioned game, but pawns are equal.}) 15... Ne8 16. Be2 (16. Rab1 Nc7
17. b4 c4 $11 {/\...Nb5}) 16... Nc7 17. Bf1 (17. Rab1 b5 18. axb6 Rxb6 19. Bf1
Rfb8 $11 {Fedorowicz John P-Kudrin New York 1983}) 17... b5 18. axb6 Rxb6 19.
Rad1 Rb4 $11 {With perfect play for Black in Ahlander,B (2424)-Marin,M (2604)
Gothenburg 2001 (0-1, 118 !)}) (13. Qc2 {is a less accurate way of developing
the queen than the main move. First of all, the queen does not cooperate with
the f4-bishop and secondly, it may get under indirect pressure along the
c-file.} Nbd7 14. Rae1 {Concentrating pieces on the kingside fails to impress
as the f-pawn is temporarily blocked by two bishops.} (14. Rfe1 Rfe8 15. Be2
Rac8 16. a5 (16. Rad1 {Poulton,J (2300)-Emms,J (2455) London 1993 (0-1, 29)} c4
) 16... c4 17. f3 Nh5 18. Be3 {This is an important moment: White does not
have Bg5. And against other retreats ...Bd4+ followed by ...Qh4 would kill.} f5
19. Qd2 Nhf6 $11) 14... c4 15. Be2 Rac8 16. Bg5 {Agzamov,G-Psakhis,L Baku 1979
(0-1, 41)} Nc5 {[%cal Ge7c7]} 17. Bxc4 Qe5 18. Bh4 (18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Rd1 Qd8
$15) 18... Rfe8 19. Bd3 Qd4 20. Rd1 Nxd3 21. Rxd3 Qc5 {folloed by ...b7-b5
