1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 {This is a
move advocated by Nimzowitsch. Before playing e2-e4 White makes sure Black
does not pin the knight with ...Bg4. But Nimzovitsch' original idea was
immediately putting pressure on d6 with Nc4, a plan examined in this line. As
for a transposition to a classical system hybrid see the next line.} Bg7 ({
If Black plans meeting the classical system with ...Re8 and ...Nbd7, the
simplest reaction is} 7... Nbd7 {so as to meet} 8. Nc4 {with} Nb6 $11 {But our
repertoire is different so we need ignoring the positional threat.}) 8. Nc4 O-O
9. Bf4 {The most active move, immediately attacking d6. There are many
possible plans, Black frequently sacrifices the pawn in order to get an
advance in development, but we will examine a solid and hardly refutable plan.}
(9. Bg5 {is best met in a similar way as the main plan.} b6 10. e3 (10. a4 Ba6
11. Nb5 Bxb5 12. axb5 Nbd7 13. e3 h6 14. Bf4 {Hyldkrog,L-From,S Denmark 1976 
(0-1, 61)} Ne5 $1 15. Bxe5 dxe5 16. d6 (16. Be2 Qe8 $5) 16... Qe8 17. Qa4 Qe6
18. Be2 Rfd8 19. O-O Bf8 {wins the pawn with just some light white
compensation on light squares.}) 10... Ba6 11. a4 h6 12. Bh4 Qe7 13. Qc2 (13.
Nb5 Bxb5 14. axb5 Nbd7 15. Be2 {Szabo,L-Portisch,L Budapest 1959 (½-½, 66)}
Ne5 $11) {Averbakh, Y-Kapengut,A Lvov 1973 (1-0, 41)} 13... Bb7 14. e4 Na6 $36)
(9. g3 {is slightly more poisoned than it may look at first sight.} Ne8 ({
Even though the pawn is not attacked, this remains a good move. The main idea
is preparing ... Nd7. The hidden dangers for Black are revealed by the
following game:} 9... b6 10. a4 Ba6 11. Nb5 Bxb5 12. axb5 Ne8 13. Bf4 Nd7 {
Quinn,M (2399)-Wojtaszek,R (2597) Turin 2006 (0-1, 33)} 14. Bg2 $1 Ne5 15. Bxe5
Bxe5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. d6 Nxd6 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. O-O Nxb5 20. e3 Qc6 21. Qd2
$14 {Black does not seem to have entirely adequate compensation for the
exchange, as his kingside is weak and does not enjoy the defense of the knight.
}) 10. Bg2 Nd7 11. a4 Nb6 {The thematic way of exchanging the knight.} 12. Na3
(12. Nxb6 Qxb6 13. O-O Bd7 $11) 12... Bd7 13. O-O (13. a5 Nc8 14. Nc4 Rb8 15.
O-O Qc7) 13... Nxa4 (13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nxa4 15. c4 $36 {Loetscher,R (2417)
-Fier,A (2572) Basel 2014 (0-1, 41)}) 14. Nxa4 b5 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. e4 Nd6 {
AN interesting position with mutual crushing pawn majorities. Black's pawns
are nos lower than White's. One important issue is the passive a3-knight.} 17.
Bf4 Qb6 18. Qd2 a5 19. e5 b4 $132) 9... Ne8 {Black defends the pawn and
prepares to exchange the active knight with ...b7-b6 and ...Ba6.} 10. Qd2 (10.
e3 b6 11. Nb5 Ba6 12. Nbxd6 Nxd6 13. Bxd6 Re8 14. Bg3 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 b5 16. Be2
Bxb2 17. Rb1 Bc3+ 18. Kf1 a6 19. Rc1 Qf6 20. Bf3 (20. Qc2 $2 Rxe3 21. Bf3 Rxf3
22. gxf3 Qxf3 23. Rg1 Bd4 $17) 20... c4 21. Bc7 Ra7 22. d6 Be5 23. h4 Rxc7 24.
dxc7 Bxc7 $44) (10. Nb5 a6 11. Nbxd6 Nxd6 12. Bxd6 (12. Nxd6 g5 13. Bg3 f5 $17)
12... Re8 13. Bf4 {White needs being ready to defend the king with Bd2.} (13.
Bg3 b5 14. Nd6 Bxb2 $17) 13... Nd7 14. e3 Nf6 $15 15. d6 $2 b5 $19 16. Ne5 Qa5+
17. Qd2 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Ne4+ $19) (10. e4 Nd7 $5 $146 11. Be2 (11. Bxd6 Nxd6 12.
Nxd6 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qf6 $17) (11. Nxd6 $2 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qf6 $17) 11... Nb6 12.
O-O Nxc4 13. Bxc4 a6 14. a4 f5 $11) 10... b6 11. a4 ({Once again White should
not toy around with development.} 11. Nb5 Ba6 12. Nbxd6 $2 Nxd6 13. Nxd6 g5 14.
Bg3 f5 $17) 11... Ba6 12. e3 (12. Nb5 {gains space but offers Black a target
on b5.} Bxb5 13. axb5 Nd7 14. e3 (14. Nxd6 Nxd6 15. Bxd6 Re8 $15 16. Bf4 Nf6
17. d6 $2 Ne4 18. Qd3 $2 Bxb2 $19) 14... Ne5 $1 {Hoping to get the perfect
blocking d6-square for the other knight.} 15. Bxe5 (15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Bg3 Nd6
$15) 15... Bxe5 16. Be2 (16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Be2 Nd6 $15) 16... Bg7 17. O-O Nc7
18. Na3 Qd7 19. Rab1 (19. Ra2 {Gligoric,S-Giustolisi,A Dublin 1957 (½-½, 31)}
a6 $1 {Now and in other similar moments White fails keeping the queenside
blocked.} 20. bxa6 (20. Nc4 Rfb8 21. bxa6 b5 22. Na5 Rxa6 23. Rfa1 Rba8 24. Ra3
Qf5 $17) 20... b5 21. Rfa1 Rxa6 $15) 19... a6 20. Qd3 axb5 21. Nxb5 Ra4 (21...
Nxb5 22. Qxb5 Qxb5 23. Bxb5 $15) 22. b3 Ra2 23. Nxc7 Qxc7 24. Qb5 Bf6 25. Bf3
Rfa8 26. Rfd1 Kg7 27. g3 h5 $15 {Halkias,S (2519)-Papaioannou,I (2591) Athens
2001 (½-½, 76)}) (12. e4 Qe7 13. f3 Nd7 $5 $11) 12... f5 13. Nb5 (13. h4 Bxc4
14. Bxc4 a6 15. Be2 (15. Qe2 Nf6 16. Bd3 Ra7 17. g3 {0-1 (60) Borisenko,
G-Boleslavsky,I Moscow 1961} Nh5 $11) 15... Nd7 16. e4 fxe4 17. h5 {0-1 (46)
Farago,I (2420)-Velimirovic,D (2525) Amsterdam 1976} Bxc3 18. bxc3 Qf6 19. Bg3
Ng7 20. hxg6 hxg6) 13... Bxb5 14. axb5 Nd7 15. Be2 Ne5 (15... Qf6 16. h4 {
offers White some time to fight for the initiative, Thorbergsson,F (2320)
-Forintos,G (2480) Reykjavik 1974 (0-1, 35)}) 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. O-O Bg7 18. Ra2
Nc7 19. Na3 Qd7 20. Rfa1 a6 21. bxa6 b5 22. Nc2 Ra7 23. h4 Rfa8 $11 *

