1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. e4 {
This is the most typical plan connected with Nimzovitsch' "knight pirouette".
White switches back to the classical system after having avoided ...Bg4.} O-O
9. Be2 ({After} 9. Be2 Re8 10. O-O {play would transpose to the normal
classical lines with ...Re8. But since White has willingly retreated with his
knight, Black has a series of alternatives. He can use the available tempo and
(as in the main line below) even the e8-square.}) 9... Ne8 $5 {Not only
over-defending the not attacked d6-pawn but also clearing the path for the
f-pawn.} 10. O-O f5 {Aiming at eliminating once and forever White's main
long-term threat, e4-e5.} 11. exf5 {In view of the positional threat ...f5-f4,
yielding Black perfect control on e5, there is nothing better.} (11. a4 f4 12.
Nc4 (12. Bg4 {eventully exchanges the "bad" bishop but wastes time and does
not reduce the effectiveness of Black's plan:} Nd7 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5
15. Bxc8 Qxc8 16. f3 g5 17. Ne2 b6 18. Ra3 a6 19. Bd2 Nf6 20. Bc3 Nd7 {with
perfect play for Black, Horvath, J (2305)-Bagonyai, A (2260) Hungary 1997 
(½-½, 44)}) 12... Nd7 13. Bd2 (13. Ra3 Ne5 14. f3 g5 15. Bd2 Nxc4 16. Bxc4
Bd4+ 17. Kh1 Nf6 18. Rb3 Be5 19. Ne2 Nd7 20. a5 Bg7 21. Nc1 Ne5 $15 {Horvath,J
(2270)-Bagonyai,A (2260) Hungary 1995 (½-½, 60) Same players, same
evaluation.}) 13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Rb1 Qh4 16. f3 g5 17. Be1 Qh5 {
with initiative, Manojlovic,S (2166) -Juhasz,L (2233) Hungary 2003 (0-1, 18)})
(11. Nc4 f4 12. e5 ({It's now or never.} 12. g3 g5 {does not change anything
dynamically.}) 12... dxe5 $6 ({This offers White some chances. It looks more
logical to get rid of the the bad bishop with} 12... Bxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bf3
Nd6 15. Re1 Re8 {with an extra pawn and a solid blockade on dark squares.}) 13.
Bf3 Nd6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne4 Qb6 16. Bd2 Bf5 17. Bc3 $44 {½-½ Farago,I 
(2520)-Wedberg,T (2455) Osterskars 1995}) (11. f4 {Kuzenkov,A (2315)-Mathias,M
(2370) ICCF corr 1995 (½-½, 42) restricts the c1-bishop.} fxe4 12. Ndxe4 Na6
13. Ng5 Nac7 {defending the e6-square and getting ready for the queenside
attack.}) (11. Nf3 $146 f4 12. g3 g5 13. gxf4 gxf4 14. Kh1 Nd7 15. Rg1 Kh8 16.
Qd2 Ne5 17. b3 Bg4 {The most active way to fight for the blockade.} 18. Nxe5
Bxe2 19. Nxe2 Bxe5 20. Bb2 Bxb2 21. Qxb2+ Qf6 22. Qxf6+ Nxf6 23. f3 Nd7 {
with comfortable play.}) 11... Bxf5 12. Nc4 {The standard move. But since
e2-e4 is not available anymore and the d6-pawn is well defended Black can
continue with his plan.} (12. Nde4 $5 {is an interesting way of fighting for
the initiative.} Na6 13. Bg5 Nf6 14. Re1 (14. Ng3 Bd7 15. Qd2 Rf7 $5 $146 16.
Rae1 Qf8 {followed by ...Nc7 and . ..Re8 offers Black a perfect regrouping.})
14... Nc7 15. Ng3 Qd7 16. a4 Rae8 17. Qd2 {Novikov,I (2490)-Nun,J (2475)
Polanica Zdroj 1989 (1-0, 29)} Ne4 18. Ncxe4 Bxe4 19. Bc4 Bf5 $11) 12... Na6 {
Black does not need too much creativity. He can threaten ...b7-b5 with ...Rb8
and if a2-a4 then ...Nb4. As simple as that. In the long run, the d5-pawn may
become weak.} 13. Bf4 {This looks very active but the bishop is exposed in the
long run.} (13. Be3 Rb8 14. a4 Nb4 15. Rc1 b6 16. Qd2 a6 (16... Rb7 $5 17. Bg5
Bf6 18. Bf4 {Gurevich,M (2630) -Moskalenko,V (2475) Belgrade 1988 (1-0, 39)}
Re7 19. Ne3 Bc8 20. Ng4 Bxg4 21. Bxg4 Nc7 $11 {With the e6-square safely
defended and the d5-paw under pressure Black is doing fine.}) 17. Bg5 {Zlotnik,
B (2440)-Pigusov,E (2530) Belgrade 1988 (½-½, 31)} Bf6 18. h4 Qd7 {Planning .
..Bd4. The exchange on f6 may turn h2-h4 into a weakening move.}) (13. Ne3 Bd7
14. Bd2 ({If} 14. Ng4 {as in Navarovszky,L (2315)-Palkovi,J (2405) Hungary
1993 (½-½, 33) Black should ignore the threat Nh6+:} Nac7 15. Nh6+ Kh8 16. a4
Qh4 17. g3 Qd4 $11) (14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Ng3 Nac7 16. a4 Qh4 $15 {Peng,Z (2370)
-Madl,I (2420) Belgrade 1994 (1-0, 62) With active play on both wings.}) 14...
Rb8 15. Ng4 Nac7 16. a4 a6 17. Qc1 Bxg4 18. Bxg4 Nf6 19. Bh3 b5 $132 {
Lukasiewicz,G (2320)-Foisor,O (2455) Cannes 1990 (½-½, 28)}) (13. a3 {
a somewhat mysterious ove.} Rb8 14. Bf4 b5 15. Ne3 c4 16. a4 {Korobov,A (2663)
-Kurmann,O (2432) Rijeka 2010 (1-0, 22)} b4 17. Nb5 Bxb2 {with hhuge
complications and balnced chances.}) (13. Bg4 {offers a generally favourable
exchange as e6 is weak, but allows Black activating his play:} Nac7 14. Bxf5
Rxf5 15. Ne3 {Schneider,A (2385)-Tolnai,T (2500) Hungary 1991 (1-0, 30)} Rh5
$15 {Keeping the pressure on d5 and creating some kingside threats.}) 13... Rb8
14. Bg3 (14. Qd2 b5 15. Bg5 Nf6 16. Ne3 Bd7 $11 {½-½ Sutter,O (2336)-Kurmann,
O (2412) Switzerland 2014}) (14. a4 Nb4 15. Rc1 a6 $132) 14... b5 15. Ne3 {
Browne,W (2555)-Gurevich,D (2490) Palma de Mallorca 1989 (1-0, 39)} b4 (15...
Nac7 16. Nxf5 gxf5 17. Qd2 Nf6 {is also interesting.}) 16. Nb5 Qd7 17. a4 Bxb2
18. Ra2 Bf6 {with very unclear play.} *

