pawn on e3 instead of e4 does not improve White's position.} 10. Be2 (10. Qb3
Bxf3 11. gxf3 b6 {Since f4 is not weak anymore, Black should keep his
queenside intact.} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Nh5 14. Bg3 f5 15. f4 Nd7 {Akshat,K 
(2354)-Afek,Y (2315) Haarlem 2013 (1-0, 43)}) 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 O-O 12. O-O
Qe7 $11) ({Or if} 9. Nd2 Nh5 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nc4 f5 12. g3 Qc7 13. Bg2 Nd7 $132
) 9... O-O 10. e3 {Keeping the pawn on e3 takes out of Black's hands one of
his main ideas in the Benoni: the pressure on e4. But if Black later plays ...
f7-f5, the d5-pawn may turn weak. Black's main hero in this line (and in
modern times, in the Benoni in general) used to be Vugar Gashimov. He knew
like no other how to use Black's regrouping resources. True, wins alternated
with losses and hard draws, but his play was inspiring. On the other hand, I
cannot help thinking that he was mainly improvising in basically worse
positions. The line recommended below may look drier but surely is safer.} Ne8
{Preparing ...Nd7.} ({Gashimov also used to play} 10... Re8 {Threatening to
free Black's position with ...Ne4.} 11. Nd2 Nbd7 ({If allowed to play} 11...
Nfd7 {followed by ...Ne5, Black would transpose to the line below, but the
concrete problem is that after} 12. Bxd6 $1 Nb6 13. Bxc5 Nxd5 14. Nde4 Be6 15.
Be2 Nxc3 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Nxc3 {his compensation may not be enough.}) 12. Be2
(12. Bxd6 Nb6 $44 {is a completely different issue now as Black is better
developed.}) 12... Ne5 13. Bh2 $1 {A very nasty move.} (13. O-O Nfd7 {followed
by ...f7-f5, ...Nf7 and ...Nf6 Black is perfectly regrouped and has no
problems at all. But the last move prevents this.}) {The point is that after}
13... Nfd7 14. f4 {there is no clear way of proving compensation for the lost
piece:} Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Rxe3+ 16. Be2 $16) 11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O {Many moves have
been tried here, but I believe that only:} Ne5 $5 {offers good chances for
equalizing. The knight stands ell on e5 and after an exchange the other knight
will happily jump to d6, achieving a perfect blockade.} 13. Nd2 {The most
principled continuation, keeping all minor pieces on board. But now the
e5-knight stands perfectly well.} (13. Bxe5 Bxe5 (13... dxe5 {This may also be
good but less principled than the main answer. Why would Black keep the
bishops on board if he is playing for a blockade on dark squares?} 14. Nd2 (14.
a5 Nd6 15. Nd2 f5 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Qd6 18. Qb3 Kh8 19. Na4 Bd7 20. Nb6
Rad8 $13) 14... b6 15. Nc4 {Fodor,T (2455)-Lukac,R (2126) Banska Stiavnica
2013 (1-0, 35)} Rb8 16. Qb3 Bd7 17. Rfd1 f5 18. d6 Kh8 $132) 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15.
a5 Nd6 16. Na4 ({The critical move, attacking Black's weakness. If} 16. Qb3 Bd7
17. Qa3 Rc8 18. Rac1 {Wagner,D (2487)-Chudinovskih,A (2296) Legnica 2013 (0-1,
