1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2
O-O 9. O-O {Despite looking completely inoffensive, the Fianchetto System is
not without venom. Like in the previous line (6) White refrains from the early
occupation of the center with e2-e4, thus avoiding Black's usual counterplay
in the center. White has two main plans. One of them consists of thoroughly
preparing e2-e4-e5. If he succeeds, the bishop would stand perfectly on g2,
over defending the d5-pawn. Alternatively, he can prepare b2-b4. And of course,
the piece pressure on d6 is always an issue.} Re8 {I have almost always played
this move, considering it the most flexible. Usually, the knight goes to d7,
but in some cases, it is better to keep the possibility of ...Na6. Besides, ...
Ne4 is something White should count with.} 10. h3 {This is the third most
important move after 10.Bf4 and 10.Nd2. White prevents ...Bg4 and ...Ng4, thus
hoping to be in time for e2-e4.} (10. a4 {is an open invitation to provoke 10.
.a6 when Black does not dispose of ...Na6 anymore. But he can do better:} Ne4
11. Nxe4 Rxe4 12. Nd2 Rb4 13. Ra2 a5 14. b3 b5 15. axb5 Nd7 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Qc2
Rxb5 $11 {with active queenside counterplay, Grischuk,A (2792)-Caruana,F (2791)
Stavanger 2014 (0-1, 39).}) (10. Re1 a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. e4 {Without
controlling g4 this offers Black excellent counterplay. With the bishop on g2
the d3-square is vulnerable to a knight invasion.} (12. Bf4 Ng4 $1 $11 {
/\...Nge5} 13. Bxd6 $2 Qb6 14. Bf4 c4 15. Rf1 Qxb2 $17) 12... Ng4 13. Nd2 Nge5
14. Bf1 Nf8 $5 15. a5 (15. h3 g5 16. f4 gxf4 17. gxf4 Neg6 18. Nc4 Bd4+ 19. Kh2
Qh4 $36) (15. f4 Ng4 16. Nf3 f5 $11) 15... g5 {A typical move slowing down
White's central plan. If allowed Black could later insist with ...g5-g4 but
for the time being the main threat is ...N8g6.} 16. f4 gxf4 17. gxf4 Ng4 18.
Nf3 f5 $15 {Ding,L (2755)-Grischuk,A (2794) Tsaghkadzor 2015 (½-½, 34)}) (10.
Bf4 {is examined in Line 8.}) ({The classical main line} 10. Nd2 {is examined
in lines 9 and 10.}) 10... a6 11. a4 Ne4 {Before exposing his rook, Black
provoked the weakening of the b4-square, a typical issue.} 12. Nxe4 (12. Ra3
Nd7 13. Nxe4 (13. Qc2 Ndf6 14. Nh4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 c4 16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Qxb6 18.
Be3 $2 Rxe3 19. fxe3 Qxe3+ 20. Kh2 Nh5 $40 {Horvath,E (2220)-Marin,M (2480)/
Budapest 1990. (0-1, 26)}) 13... Rxe4 14. Nd2 Re8 15. Nc4 Nb6 (15... Ne5 16.
Ne3 f5 $5) 16. Ne3 Nd7 {½-½ Huebner,R-Tal,M Montreal 1979}) 12... Rxe4 13.
Nd2 {Preparing for the queenside fight.} (13. Bg5 {weakens the b2-pawn.} Qc7
14. Qd2 Rb4 15. Ra2 Nd7 16. b3 Rb8 17. a5 b5 $17 {1/2-1/2 Sosonko,G (2520)
-Galego,L (2360)/Novi Sad 1990.}) (13. Re1 {does not have a clear idea and
looks too slow.} Nd7 14. Qc2 Rb4 15. Ra2 b5 16. axb5 {Tkachiev,V (2672)
-Gdanski,J (2528)/Ohrid 2001 (½-½, 18)} Bb7 $1 17. bxa6 Bxd5 18. Ra3 Be4 19.
Qd1 Qb6 $15) 13... Rb4 ({Black needs controling c4 as if} 13... Re8 $2 14. Nc4
$16 {followed by Bf4 he is almost paralyzed.}) 14. Ra2 (14. Qc2 {planning Nc4
and Bd2.} Nd7 15. Nc4 Ne5 16. Ne3 b5 (16... f5 17. Ra2 (17. Bd2 $2 Rxb2) 17...
f4 $1 $36) 17. axb5 Rxb5 18. f4 Nd7 19. Kh2 Nb6 $132 {Minko,V (2216)-Gopal,G 
(2575) Nancy 2015 (½-½, 85)}) 14... b5 {Black needs restoring the
communication between his erring rook and the rest of the army even though
this may cost one pawn.} 15. axb5 Nd7 $1 {Playing in the spirit of the Volga
Gambit.} (15... Rxb5 16. Nc4 $16) 16. b3 (16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Nc3 Nb6 18. bxa6 Rxa6
19. Rxa6 Bxa6 20. Re1 Nc4 21. Qc2 Qb7 22. Ne4 {1/2-1/2 Hoffman,A (2485)-Milos,
G (2586)/Santos 2003.} Be5 $5 {defending d6 and provoking the next move.} 23.
f4 $6 Bg7 24. g4 Rb3 $36) (16. Re1 {is a neutral move basically wasting a
tempo.} Rxb5 17. e4 (17. Nc4 Ne5) 17... Rab8 18. Bf1 Rb4 19. Nc4 Ne5 20. Na5
Rd4 21. Qe2 Bd7 22. Kg2 Nd3 23. Rd1 Bb5 24. Nc6 Nxc1 {0-1 Gyorkos-Tolnai,
Hungary 1987.}) (16. bxa6 Rxa6 17. Rxa6 Bxa6 18. b3 Qa5 19. Re1 Qa2 $15 {
Offers Black simply too much play for the pawn.}) 16... a5 $1 $146 {Black
needs keeping the control over c4 for a bit more and also create the threat of
undermining it with ...a5-a4.} (16... Rxb5 $6 {Berezjuk,S (2439)-Cvek,R (2430),
Moravia 2002 (½-½, 25)} 17. Nc4 $1 Ne5 18. Na3 Rbb8 19. f4 Nd7 20. Nc4 $16)
17. Nc4 Ne5 18. Bd2 (18. Na3 a4 $17) 18... Rxb5 19. Na3 Rbb8 20. f4 Nd7 21. Nc4
Ba6 {Another positive effect of ...a6-a5.} 22. Nxd6 (22. Nxa5 Qb6 23. Kh2 Bb5
24. Qe1 Ra6 {leaves White hanging, with enough compensation for Black.}) (22.
Bxa5 Qe7 23. Qd3 Ra7 {With a similar evaluation.}) 22... Nb6 23. Ne4 a4 {
Black's queenside pieces are perfectly coordinated and the g7-bishop provides
some help, too. White cannot enjoy his pawn too much.} 24. bxa4 Bc4 25. Ra3
Bxd5 26. Bc3 Bxc3 27. Rxc3 c4 28. Qd4 Bxe4 29. Qxd8+ Rxd8 30. Bxe4 Rxa4 $11 *

