O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nd2 {This is the classical main move. White hopes to
consolidate his knight on c4, of course, but things are not that simple.} a6
11. a4 Nbd7 12. Nc4 {As it turns out soon, this is premature.} (12. Qb3 {
aims at putting early queenside pressure but Black can handle this.} Rb8 13.
Nc4 Ne5 14. Nb6 (14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. Qa3 Bf5 $15) 14... Nfd7 15. Nxc8 Qxc8 (15...
Rxc8 $5) 16. h3 (16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Qc2 c4 $132) 16... c4 (16... f5)
17. Qa3 Nc5 $15 {Glavina,P (2405)-Lacasa Diaz,J (2295) Vendrell 1993 (½-½,
24)}) (12. a5 {is an open invitation to a draw.} Rb8 $5 {is more ambitious.} (
12... b5 {This is the smplest, but Black needs being ready for a perpetual
repetition.} 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. Nb3 Nc4 15. Ra4 (15. Qd3 Rb8) 15... Nb6 16. Ra2
Nc4 {White can keep repeating moves, or try playing on with} 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18.
Bxd2 {even though after} Rb8 {Black has no problems.}) 13. Nc4 (13. h3 b5 14.
axb6 Nxb6 15. Nb3 Nc4 16. Ra4 Rb4 $1 $17) 13... Ne5 (13... b5 $2 14. axb6 Nxb6
15. Na5 $16) 14. Nb6 (14. Nxe5 Rxe5) 14... Nfd7 $5 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 $11 {With
normal Benoni play.} 16. Ne4 (16. h3 f5 17. Qc2 {Soppe,G (2435)-Mahia,G (2390)
Buenos Aires 1988 (½-½, 78)} c4 $15) (16. Qa4 f5) 16... Qc7 17. Bd2 Nf6 18.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bc3 Rb8 20. Qa4 Nd7 21. e4 Bxc3 22. bxc3 c4 $13 {Loncar,R (2405)
-Cebalo,M (2515) Genova 1998 (0-1, 40)}) (12. e4 {does not look right. ith the
bishop on g2 the d3-square remains vulnerable.} Rb8 13. Qe2 (13. Nc4 Ne5 {
may transpose to the main line.}) 13... Ne5 {Planning ...Nh5 and ...f7-f5.} 14.
f4 {Remon,A (2375)-Vilela de Acuna,J (2440) Havana 1983 (0-1, 47)} Neg4 $1 15.
h3 Nh6 16. Nc4 (16. g4 $2 Nfxg4 17. hxg4 Bd4+ 18. Rf2 Nxg4 $19) (16. Qf3 b5) (
16. a5 Nxe4 17. Ndxe4 f5 $15) 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Na5 Bd7 19. Nc6 Bxc6
20. dxc6 Nf5 $1 $13) (12. Ra2 {is a contorted way of trying neutralizing the
g7-bishop.} Rb8 13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Nxb6 15. b3 h5 $5 {Just one of the playable
ideas.} 16. Nf3 (16. Nde4 Nbxd5 $17) (16. Qc2 h4 17. gxh4 Nh5 18. Nf3 Bxc3 19.
Qxc3 Nxd5 20. Qc4 Nb4 21. Ra3 Be6) (16. Bb2 h4 17. gxh4 Nh5 $15 {Bob, Axel}) ({
The point is that} 16. h3 {runs into} h4 17. g4 $2 Nxg4 $1) {Shapiro,D (2350)
-Fedorowicz,J (2525) Somerset 1986 (0-1, 37)} 16... Na8 $5 $132 {Now that Nc4
is not an issue anymore, this regrouping is well timed. Black plans ...Nc7-b5.}
) 12... Ne5 ({The main alternative is} 12... Nb6 {but the recommended move is
not only more active but also lads to more coherent play. First of all, it
does not block the own b-pawn.}) 13. Nxe5 {This exchange frees Black's play 
(as usual) but avoiding it hands in Black the initiative.} (13. Na3 Nh5 $5 {
offers Black counterplay all over the board. The main threat is gaining space
