Nxd6 Rd8 27. Rfxc1 Rxd6 28. e5 Rd8 29. exf6 Bxf6 30. Rxc5 Rxb2 $44 {Yuffa,D 
(2373)-Shariyazdanov,A (2584)/Izhevsk 2013/CBM 155 Extra (1/2, 43)}) 23... h6 {
A half-waiting and useful move, probably planning ...g6-g5. This way, Black
could later play ...Nfd7, without fearing f2-f4 anymore. Besides, in some
lines when his rooks would leave the back rank undefended on being sent on
active missions, the h7-square might come in handy to the king.} ({The
straightforward} 23... Nfd7 {was very much OK in Grischuk, A (2760)-Vocaturo,
D (2581) Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (1-0, 44).} 24. f4 Nf3+ 25. Kf2 (25. Bxf3 Rxf3
26. Nc4 Rxe4 27. Ra8+ Bf8 28. Nxd6 Re2 $132) 25... Nh4 26. Nc4 Bd4+ 27. Kf1 (
27. Rxd4 cxd4 28. Nxd6 Reb8 $36) 27... Rg3 28. Nxd6 $5 Rb8 $1 (28... Rxg2 $2 {
Underestimating the force of White's counterattack.} 29. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 30. Nxe8
$18 {Suddenly, there is no attack left for Black, but his king is in deadly
danger. Grischuk,A (2760)-Vocaturo,D (2581) Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (1-0, 45)})
29. Rd2 (29. Bh1 Rxh3 30. Bg2 Rh2 $17) 29... Nxg2 30. Rxg2 Rxh3 $132 {[%csl
Gb2][%cal Gh3h1] is at least OK for Black.}) (23... Reb8 $5 {looks like a good
alternative.}) 24. Nc2 $2 {Both players agreed that this immediately put White
into an unpleasant position. According to Ponomariov, this mistake was
provoked by miscalculation. His obvious idea was inhibiting ...g6-g5 in view
of Ne3-f5. True, it is not easy to suggest a useful move for White, that is
the main problem.} (24. Kf1 {may be useful in some cases, by defending e2, but
in the following logical sequence, the king will be placed badly:} g5 (24...
Nd3 25. Nc4) 25. Nc2 Nd3 26. Ra4 Nd7 27. Ne3 Nxc1 28. Rxc1 Rxb2 29. Nf5 Bd4 {
Suddenly, the king is in some trouble.} 30. Nxd4 cxd4 31. Rxd4 Ra8 {with
fantastic compensation for the pawn.}) 24... Nd3 ({Ponomariov had considered
also} 24... Nc4 25. Ra2 Nxe4 26. Ra4 $13 Bxb2 $2 27. Re1 $16) 25. Ra4 ({
Ponomariov's first intention was} 25. Ra3 {but he overlooked} Nxc1 $1 ({
He had relied on} 25... Nxb2 26. Rxb3 Nxd1 27. Rd3 $18 {trapping the knight.})
26. Rxc1 Rxb2 {White does not seem to get enough play with} 27. Ne3 Nxe4 28.
Bxe4 Rxe4 29. Nc4 Rbe2 30. Nxd6 Rf4 {and the king is in a dangerous situation.}
) 25... Nd7 26. Ra6 Nxc1 27. Rxc1 Bxb2 28. Rd1 Be5 29. Na3 Nb6 $17 {Ponomariov,
R (2756)-Bacrot, E (2723) Elancourt 2013 (0-1, 58) Black has got everything he
could dream of in the Benoni. Opposite-coloured bishops, active pieces, the
passed c-pawn...} *

