1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 ({White does
best including this move. If} 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 {Black gets a
comfortable version of the ...Bg4 classical system (see Database 1). For
instance,:} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7 12. Bf4 Qe7 13. Qe2 a6 14. a4 Rfe8 15.
Rae1 Rac8 {Preparing the usual counterplay with ...c5-c4.}) 7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O
9. Bd3 {Starting with 1990 when Alburt introduced a novelty discovered by his
friend Chernin (see Line 2), this system caused Black lots of troubles for
more than a decade. White's setup is very ambitious: he safely defends e4,
allowing him to avoid Nd2 as in the classical system and also prevents the
freeing ...Bg4. The only drawback of this variation is that the king remains
in the center for one more love than usual, allowing the following move:} b5 $1
{I tend to build up my repertoire (which I many times share with the readers)
based on positional systems, without the need of analyzing nd memorizing long
forced variations. The last move is an exception, but no matter as long as I
have tried, I could not find entirely viable counterplay after normal
developing moves.} (9... a6 10. a4 (10. O-O b5 11. a3 Nbd7 12. Bf4 {followed
by Qd2 and b2-b4 is also more pleasant for White.}) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 (
11... Nh5 {is an interesting attempt at counterplay. Playing with white, I
introduced the pradoxical} 12. Be2 {against Gheorghiu in 1989. I still find
this the most discouraging way of meeting the early knight jump, as White
prevents ...Ne5 and prepares ...Be3 followed by Nd2, but strangely it has
never been popular.}) 12. Bf4) 10. Bxb5 {After the first fury caused by
Alburt's/Chernin's innovation, this has become the main line for quite some
time, as it suddenly appeared that Black's way to a draw was not all roses
despite simplifications.} ({Since Black has played ...b7-b5 without wasting
time with ...a7-a6, White can't hope for an advantage by ignoring the pawn.} 
10. O-O b4 11. Ne2 (11. Na4 Ba6 12. a3 c4 13. Bb1 b3 $5 {leves the b1-bishop
and the a1-rook as mere spectators.}) 11... Re8 12. Ng3 Ba6 $1 {Since the
white knights are far from the c4-square White has no obvious way of
maintaining the blockade on c4.} 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qd3 (14. Nd2 c4 $1 $15)
14... Qc8 15. Qc4 Nd7 16. Rb1 Nb6 17. Qc2 c4 $15 {With great queenside play in
Olszewski,M (2554)-Gdanski,J (2511) Katowice 2014 (½-½, 27)}) (10. a3 b4 11.
axb4 cxb4 12. Nb5 (12. Na4 Re8 {leaves the knight passive on a4, Kasantsev, A 
(2015)-Ibadov,D (2173) Voronezh 2015 (0-1, 20)}) (12. Ne2 Re8 13. Ng3 a5 14.
O-O Ba6 15. Nd4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 {Khenkin,I (2609)-Bar,R (2381) Tel Aviv 2001 
(½-½, 53)} Nfd7 $15 {With queenside initiative and dangerous pawn majority.})
12... Ba6 13. O-O Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Nxe4 $11 15. Qe1 $2 {Missing a tactical trick.}
Ng3 16. fxg3 Qb6+ 17. Kh2 Qxb5 $17 {Evdokimov,A (2545)-Predojevic,B (2650)
Budva 2009 (0-1, 40)}) (10. Nxb5 {Will be examined in Lines 2 and 3.}) 10...
Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 14. N2c4 {The end of the forced
variation. Black is better developed and the d5-pawn is weak, while the b2-
and a2-pawns are under pressure. But the white knights are quite troublesome,
preventing the desirable check on e8. Black needs playing accurately for a few
moves at least. As we will see, this variation has made the correspondence
players' delight.} Nd7 15. O-O Ne5 {Popularized by the late talented
grandmaster Vugar Gashimov.} ({The old line went} 15... Nb6 {but nowadays it
seems to offer White better chances for an advantage than the main move.}) 16.
Nxc8 {White needs eliminating the bishop; otherwise he could not claim any
shadow of an advantage..} (16. Nxe5 Qxd6 17. Nc4 (17. Nc6 Bb7 18. Be3 Bxb2 $5
$146 19. Rb1 Bxc6 20. dxc6 Bd4 $11) 17... Qa6 18. Qb3 Bb7 19. Rd1 Bd4 20. Ne3 {
½-½ Wang, Y (2736)-Gashimov, V (2704) Kallithea 2008 Correspondence players
were a bit more curious to check how things could go on.} Rfd8 21. Bd2 Rab8 22.
Qc2 Bxd5 23. Nxd5 {1/2-1/2 (23) Neuer,T (2425)-Eschenko,V ICCF email 2007} Rxd5
24. Bc3 Qd6 $15 {With a domiating position in the centre, although White
should be able to hold.}) 16... Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 {White has a couple of
tempi available until the d5-pawn will be put under real pressure. He needs
using them for completing the development, but this is not simple as moving
any of the queenside pieces would cost at least a pawn.} 18. Re1 (18. Qf3 Rfe8
$1 ({For some hidden reasons this threatens ...Bh2+, which does not work
immediately:} 18... Bh2+ $2 19. Kxh2 Qxf1 20. Bh6 $16 Qxa1 $2 21. Qf6) 19. Rd1
(19. Rb1 $2 Bh2+ $1 20. Kxh2 Qxf1 $17 {Andonovski,L (2326)-Jianu,V (2545)
Tivat 2011 (0-1, 42) Black has won an exchange as} 21. Bh6 {is parried with}
Qe2 22. Qf6 Qe5+) (19. Bf4 Bxb2 20. Rad1 {Gstach,J (2042)-Kliegl,S (1865)
Untersiebenbrunn 2012 (0-1, 36)} Qe2 21. Qxe2 Rxe2 22. d6 Rd8 $11 23. d7 $2 Bd4
$17) 19... c4 20. a4 (20. Rb1 Qxa2 21. Bg5 Bxb2 22. Rxb2 Qxb2 23. d6 Red8 24.
d7 Rb8 25. Bxd8 Rxd8 26. Qe4 {Kanter,E (2371)-Kuznetsov,M (2147) Gornozavodsk
2009 (1-0, 31)} c3 27. Qe8+ Kg7 28. Qxd8 c2 29. Rf1 c1=Q 30. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 31. Kh2
Qf4+ {with a perpetual.}) 20... Qb7 21. Ra3 Bxb2 22. d6 Qxf3 23. Rxf3 Bxc1 24.
Rxc1 Red8 $11 {Shengelia,D (2560)-Gashimov,V (2740) Novi Sad 2009 (½-½, 47)})
(18. Bg5 Bxb2 19. Be7 Rfe8 $11 20. d6 $2 Bxa1 21. Qxa1 {Rakic,M (2354)
-Stojanovic,A (2313) Kragujevac 2015 (½-½, 29)} Red8 22. Rd1 (22. Bxd8 Rxd8
$17) 22... Rd7 $17) 18... Rfe8 19. Bg5 {White cannot delay this endlessly.} (
19. Rb1 Qxa2) 19... Bd4 {Cutting off the pawns. The game is close enough to a
draw, but WHite can still try outtricking the opponent, so a few more accurate
moves are needed.} (19... Bxb2 $2 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. d6 $18 {Zlender,B-Strbad,
F ICCF email 1992 (1-0, 28) I do not remember how weak computers were in 1992,
but still, the feeling is Black set up the wrong position on board when taking
on b2.}) 20. Rc1 (20. Rb1 Qd6 21. Qa4 (21. Qf3 Bxb2 22. g4 {Acevedo Villalba,A
(2528)-Soltau,A (2625) ICCF email 2008 (½-½, 43)} Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Be5 24. Qe4
f6 25. Be3 Rd8 26. f4 Bc3 27. Rc1 Bd4 28. Bxd4 cxd4 29. Qxd4 Qxd5 30. Qxf6 Rf8
31. Qe5 Qf3 32. Rc3 Qxf4 $11) 21... Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Qxd5 23. Bh6 Qd8 24. b3 (24.
Qxa7 Ra8 25. Qb7 Rxa2 26. Qe4 Ra8 27. Bg5 Qc8) 24... c4 25. bxc4 Bxf2+ $1 {
A trick Black should always be aware of.} 26. Kxf2 Qh4+ 27. Kf1 Qxh6 $11 {
Mahnke,R (2354)-Mueller,G (2340) GER email 2007 (½-½, 32)}) (20. Be7 Bxf2+ $1
21. Kxf2 Rxe7 22. Rxe7 Qf6+ 23. Qf3 Qxe7 24. Rd1 Rd8 25. Qf4 Kg7 26. b3 Qf6 27.
Kg3 Qc3+ 28. Kh2 Qf6 29. Kg3 Qc3+ 30. Kh2 {½-½ Potapov,A (2426)-Simacek,P 
(2532) Pardubice 2010}) 20... Qd6 {Attacking and blocking the pawn. Could we
ask for more?} 21. Qa4 Re5 22. Rxe5 Qxe5 23. Qd7 Rb8 24. Bh6 Bxf2+ $1 $146 {
Once again this is the safest.} (24... g5 $6 25. Qg4 $1) (24... Qf6 $6 25. Rc2
Rd8 26. Qc7 Rxd5 27. Re2 {offered White dangerous initiative in Meier,G (2664)
-Gashimov,V (2740) Novi Sad 2009 (0-1, 42)}) 25. Kxf2 g5 $1 {The bishop is
almost trapped and the king is in danger. The main threats are ...Qf6+, ...
Qf4+ or simply ...Rxb2+.} 26. Rf1 (26. Bxg5 Rxb2+ 27. Kg1 Qxg5 28. Qg4 Qxg4 29.
hxg4 Rxa2 30. Rxc5 $11) (26. Rd1 Rxb2+ 27. Kg1 Rxg2+ 28. Kxg2 Qe2+ 29. Kg3 Qe3+
$11) (26. Rb1 $2 Qd4+ 27. Kf1 Qd3+ $19) 26... Qd4+ 27. Kg3 Qe5+ 28. Kf2 (28.
Kg4 $2 Rb4+ {mates}) 28... Qd4+ 29. Ke1 Qe3+ {with perpetual check. I
recommend retaining some reference points in this line. True, the position
after the opening is basically drawn, but the one who needs being accurate is
Black.} *

