1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. Bd3 b5 10. Nxb5 Re8 $1 ({Decades ago,} 10... Nxe4 {was considered
entirely playable until the following game was played:} 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 {
Alburt,L (2530)-De Firmian,N (2560) Jacksonville 1990 (1-0, 42) The point is
that} h6 {runs into} 13. Ne6 $1 {A nice trick discovered by Chernin!}) {
In this section, we will examine the lines where White defends the e4-pawn,
directly or indirectly.} 11. Nd2 (11. Bg5 {pins the knight, but loses too much
time.} c4 $1 12. Bxc4 (12. Bc2 {leaves the b5-knight undefended allowing} Qa5+
13. Nc3 Nxe4 $36) (12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Bc2 {Moullier,I (2023)-Meng,J (2095)
Chambery 2002 (½-½, 21)} Bxb2 $15) 12... Rxe4+ 13. Be2 Qa5+ 14. Nd2 (14. Nc3
Nxd5 15. O-O Nxc3 16. bxc3 Nd7 $11) 14... Ba6 15. a4 (15. Nc3 Bxe2 16. Nxe2
Nbd7 17. O-O Ree8 {retrieves the d5-pawn with comfortable play.}) 15... Bxb5
16. axb5 Rxe2+ $5 17. Kxe2 Qxb5+ 18. Ke1 Qxb2 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Ra3 Nd7 $17 {
With a pawn for the exchange and a strong attack against the uncastled king,
Pham,M (2480)-Navrotescu,C (2402) France 2007 (½-½, 51)}) (11. Nc3 {This is
basically losing time with moving around with the same piece, so little wonder
that Black is doing great after it.} Nxe4 $1 12. Nxe4 (12. Bxe4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3
Rxe4+ 14. Be3 Ba6 {leaves the d5-pawn vulnerable and the king in the centre.})
12... f5 13. Bg5 (13. Nfg5 $6 {This leaves White hanging.} fxe4 14. Bc4 (14.
Nxe4 Bf5 15. f3 Qh4+ {with strong initiative for the pawn.}) (14. Bxe4 Bxb2 $1)
14... e3 (14... Bxb2 15. Ne6 Bc3+ 16. Bd2 Qf6 17. O-O Bxe6 18. dxe6 Bxa1 19.
Bd5 Bd4 20. Bxa8 Qxe6 $17 {Komljenovic,D (2470)-Marin,M (2530) Zaragoza 1994 
(0-1, 37)}) 15. Ne6 Qh4 $17 {Efimov,I (2525)-Martorelli,A (2405) Cutro 1998 
(0-1, 48)}) 13... Qd7 14. Nfd2 fxe4 15. Nxe4 (15. Be2 {Szczepaniak,A-Sapis,W
Poland 1993 (½-½ 27)} Na6 $5 $146 16. O-O Nb4 17. Nc4 Ba6 $15) {Sanikidze,T 
(2553)-Chatalbashev,B (2552) Baden-Baden 2013 (1-0, 41)} 15... Qf5 16. Qe2 Nd7
17. g4 Qf8 18. O-O Ne5 19. f3 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Rb8 $44 {White's extra pawn is not
threatening yet and his king is exposed. The black bishops are quite active,
without being bothered by the stable knight.}) ({For} 11. O-O {[%emt 0:00:03]
see Line}) {The last move has solidly defended e4 but there is a problem now
with the other pawn.} 11... Nxd5 12. Nc4 {White should hurry creating threats
on d6, as otherwise Black would achieve easy play with natural moves.} (12. O-O
Nc7 13. Nxc7 Qxc7 14. Nc4 Nc6 15. Bf4 Re6 $11 {The control over d4 and the
long diagonal compensate for the weaknesses along the d-file.}) 12... Re6 13.
Be2 {Once again White can do better than castling. The last move removes the
bishop from an exposed square. With the king on e1 still, the bishop is
overdefended which is essential in the lines involving ...Ba6.} (13. O-O Nb4 (
13... Nc7 $6 {is less accurate than in the similar line above, as the
c1-bishop is alive already:} 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Nxc7 Qxc7 16. f4 $36) 14. Be2 Ba6
{The d6-pawn is taboo as the e2-bishop is hanging.} 15. Nc3 Nd7 16. Be3 Nb6 17.
Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Re1 (18. a3 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Nc6 20. Nd5 Qb7 21. f3 Rb8 22. Rab1 Qb3
$11) 18... Rae8 $15 {Shishkin,V (2530)-Kononenko,D (2513) Kharkov 2007 (0-1,
43)}) (13. Nbxd6 Ba6 14. O-O Nb4 15. Bb1 (15. Be2 Rxd6 16. Nxd6 Bxe2 17. Qxe2
Qxd6 18. Rd1 Bd4 19. Be3 Nd7 $15) 15... N4c6 {White has won the pawn but he is
terribly hanging and his queenside undeveloped.} 16. Qd5 Nd7 17. Rd1 (17. Qxc6
Bxc4) {Voll,A (2514)-Betker,J (2366) ICCF email 2007 (0-1, 61)} 17... Nb6 18.
Nxb6 Qxb6 $17 {/\...Rd8.} 19. Nc4 Qb4 20. Ne3 Be2 21. a3 Qa5 22. Rd2 Rd8 $19)
13... Nb6 14. Ncxd6 (14. O-O Ba6 {leads to a familiar picture.}) 14... Ba6 {
Black has played all the usual moves but White has a spare tempo to try
stabilizing. The king's presence in the center prevents him from achieving
that, though.} 15. Bg4 (15. Bf4 Nc6 16. O-O Qe7 17. Bg4 Re5 $1 18. Bxe5 Bxe5
19. f4 Bxd6 20. Qxd6 (20. Nxd6 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 Qf6 22. Qd2 Rd8 23. e5 Nxe5 24.
Ne4 Qe7 $17) 20... Bxb5 21. Qxe7 Nxe7 22. Rfc1 c4 $11) (15. Be3 Nc6 16. Bxc5
Bxb2 17. Rb1 Be5 18. O-O Bxd6 19. Nxd6 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 Rxd6 21. Bxd6 Qxd6 $15 {
Lehnhoff,H (2014) -Meyer,K (2267) GER email 2009 (½-½, 41)}) 15... f5 16. Be2
{White has wasted two tempi but he now has some chances along the a2-g8
diagonal.} Nc6 (16... Bxb5 $6 {retrieves the pawn but leaves White with two
strong bishops:} 17. Nxb5 Qxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Rxe4+ 19. Be3 Bxb2 20. Rb1 Rb4 21. Bf3
{Hauser,J (2377) -Morosi,D (2082) ICCF email 2012 (1-0, 50)}) {Black threatens
...Nd4 putting White under unbearable pressure so the next moves are forced.}
17. Be3 $1 Nd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Qb3 c4 20. Nxc4 Bxb5 21. Qxb5 Rxe4 22. Nxb6
Qxb6 23. O-O Qxb5 {½-½ Simeonov, L (2195)-Holtrop, B ICCF email 2013 The
opposite-colored bishops ending does not offer chances to any of the players.}
