1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. Bd3 b5 10. Nxb5 Re8 11. O-O {Abstractly, the most principled move.
White aims to complete his development as quickly as possible, in order to
build up an initiative based on the undeveloped black queenside. But the
obvious drawback of this variation is that the d5-pawn ill is chronically weak.
If Black manages to extinguish the initiative he might even be better. But as
a general rule White exchanges the d5-pawn for the d6-pawn, resulting in a
position where Black's activity compensates for the isolated queenside pawns.}
Nxe4 12. Re1 {In the similar lines with 10...Nxe4, White would not dispose
over this way of exchanging one of the not so many developed black pieces.} (
12. Qa4 {exposes the knight to a pin:} Bd7 13. Re1 a6 14. Qa3 Bf5 15. Bf4 Nd7
16. Nxd6 Nxd6 17. Bxd6 Qb6 18. Bxf5 gxf5 19. Be7 Bxb2 20. Qa4 Bxa1 21. Qxd7 Bc3
22. Re3 Qb1+ 23. Kh2 Qb8+ 24. g3 Ra7 25. Qxf5 Raxe7 26. Rxc3 Qd6 27. Rc4 f6 {
White has adequate compensation for the exchange but hardly more than that.}
28. Nh4 Qe5 29. Rxc5 Qxf5 30. Nxf5 Re2 {With an equal ending, Schubert, V 
(1956)-Somogyi, G (1844) LSS email 2013 (½-½, 39)}) (12. Qb3 a6 13. Na3 ({
The thematic retreat as} 13. Nc3 {absolves Black from the worries regarding
the central knight.} Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 15. Bg5 Qa5 16. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 17. Rxe1 Bxc3
18. Re8+ Kg7 $11) 13... Nd7 14. Nc4 Rb8 15. Qc2 f5 16. Re1 Nb6 17. Nxb6 Qxb6
18. Nd2 (18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Rxe4 Bb7 $15 {retrieves the pawn soon keeping two
active bishops.}) {Dano,J-Wurschner,M Slovakia 2001 (0-1, 30)} 18... Qb4 19.
Re2 Qd4 {with active play.}) (12. Bxe4 Rxe4 {is double-edged. White gains a
tempo but the weakness of the d5-pawn becomes even more relevant.} 13. Ng5 (13.
Bg5 Qd7 {A typical move, attacking the knight and keeping bot wings under
control.} 14. Nc3 Re8 15. Re1 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Bb7 17. Qd2 Na6 $11 {Ochoa de la
Rosa,M (2261)-Palmero Martinez,R (2113) Varadero 2016 (1-0, 50)}) (13. Re1
Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 Ba6 15. Bg5 Qd7 16. Nc3 Bb7 17. Qd2 Na6 {transposes to the
previous line.}) 13... Re7 ({The active} 13... Rb4 {is also viable, but
sharper.} 14. Qf3 Bf5 15. g4 Rxb5 16. gxf5 Qe7 17. Bd2 Nd7 18. Rae1 Qf6 $11)
14. Re1 (14. Bf4 Ba6 $15) 14... a6 15. Nc3 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Nd7 17. Nge4 Ne5 18.
Bg5 f6 19. Bf4 Nf7 20. Nd2 Ra7 $15 {With perfect regrouping and the healthier
structure, Namgilov, S (2425) -Berelowitsch, A (2505) Orel 1996 (1-0, 22)})
12... a6 {Once again, as in other previous lines, this intermediate move frees
Black's play.} 13. Na3 Nf6 14. Rxe8+ {Forcing Black to misplace one of his
pieces.} (14. Nc4 {is less dangerous.} Rxe1+ 15. Nxe1 Bb7 16. Bf4 Bf8 17. Ne3
Nbd7 18. Be2 Qe7 $15 {Nepomniachtchi,I (2703)-Ponkratov,P (2584) Moscow 2013 
(1-0, 74)}) 14... Nxe8 15. Bg5 ({More natural and active than} 15. Nc4 Nd7 16.
Bd2 Bb7 17. Ba5 Qe7 $11) 15... Qc7 16. Qa4 {White tries hard maintaining the
initiative, consisting so far of one-ove threats.} (16. Qd2 {offers Black easy
play:} Bb7 17. Re1 Nd7 18. Bc2 Nef6 19. Bb3 Re8 {and the weakness on d5 is
likely to tell, as White does not have any shdow of initiative, Gelfand,B 
(2680)-Topalov,V (2645) Moscow 1994 (0-1, 60)}) 16... Nf6 17. Nb5 {Another
energetical move, but White has a couple of alternatives of the same kind..} (
17. Re1 Bb7 18. Bxf6 (18. Nd2 Nbd7 19. Re7 Rd8 20. Ne4 Qb8 21. Nc4 Bxd5 22.
Nexd6 Nb6 23. Nxb6 Qxd6 24. Nxd5 Qxd5 25. Qf4 Qxd3 26. Bxf6 Bxf6 {½-½ Hoenig,
B (2382)-Schulze,M (2427) IECG email 2003 The game could continue:} 27. Qxf6
Qd1+ 28. Kh2 Qd6+ {with a drawn ending.}) (18. Qh4 Nbd7 19. Nc4 Nxd5 20. Qg3
Bf8 {leaves White with problems proving his compensation for the pawn, Van de
Mortel,J (2335)-Hernandez,G (2525) Philadelphia 1998 (0-1, 39)}) 18... Bxf6 19.
Qf4 Nd7 20. Nc4 Bxd5 21. Be4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Qb8 {[%cal Gd6d5] Unpinning the
d-pawn in order to threaten . ..d6-d5.} 23. Nxd6 (23. Qd2 Qb7 {½-½ Schmidt,H
(2188)-Simeonov,L (2150) ICCF email 2011} 24. Nxd6 Qxb2 25. Qd5 Rf8 26. Re8 Ne5
27. Nxe5 Qc1+ 28. Kh2 Qf4+ {with a perpetual.}) 23... Qxb2 24. Re7 Bxe7 25.
Qxf7+ Kh8 26. Qxe7 {With both kings exposed the game is likely to end in a
draw by perpetual, for instance:} Qc1+ 27. Kh2 Qf4+ 28. g3 Qf6 29. Qxd7 Qxf3
30. Nf7+ Kg8 31. Nh6+ Kh8 $11) (17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qf4 Nd7 19. Nc4 Bb7 20. Rd1
Be7 21. Ne3 Nf6 22. Bc2 Rb8 23. Ng5 Ba8 24. b3 Qa5 {ith adequate counterplay.
The queen is ready to join the defense along the long diagonal after ...Qc3.
Saint Amour, P (1937)-Ottenweller, W (1884) IECG email 2000 (½-½, 51)}) 17...
Qd7 18. Re1 (18. Nc3 {is too mild to cause problems.} Qxa4 19. Nxa4 Nbd7 20.
Bf4 Bf8 21. Rd1 Bb7 22. Bc4 Re8 23. b3 h6 24. Bh2 {½-½ Bendana Guerrero,G 
(2464)-Rattinger,F (2670) ICCF email 2009}) (18. Bxf6 {is the start of another
series of simple threats, requiring a bit of accuracy from Black.} Bxf6 19. Re1
Bb7 20. Qf4 Be5 21. Rxe5 (21. Nxe5 dxe5 {wins a piece even though White has
some compensation.} 22. Qxe5 axb5 23. Qf6 {The least Black can do is
simplifying to a symbolically more pleasant ending with} Nc6 $5 24. dxc6 Qxc6
25. Qxc6 Bxc6 26. a3 Rd8 $11) 21... axb5 (21... dxe5 22. Nxe5 Qxd5 23. Be4 $1
$18) 22. Re1 Bxd5 23. Ng5 Nc6 ({Improving over his own previous game:} 23...
Kg7 $6 24. Qd2 {Threatening both Bxb5 and Bxg6.} b4 25. Bxg6 hxg6 26. Qxd5 Ra6
27. Qc4 d5 28. Qh4 {1-0 Babula,V (2584) -Simacek,P (2501) Prague 2007}) 24.
Bxb5 Qf5 25. Qxf5 gxf5 26. Bxc6 Bxc6 27. Rd1 Rxa2 28. Rxd6 Be4 $11 {Polak,T 
(2553)-Simacek,P (2493) Decin 2009 (½-½, 37)}) 18... Nxd5 {The last accurate
move.} (18... Bb7 $6 19. Qh4 $1 {offers White the initiative.}) 19. Qb3 (19.
Be4 Bb7 $17 20. Nc3 Bc6 {leaves Black with an extra pawn.}) 19... axb5 20. Bxb5
Nc6 21. Qxd5 Bb7 {Mterial is equal and both sides have normal development. The
queen stands actively on d5, but it is also exposed.} 22. a4 Nb4 $1 23. Qxc5
dxc5 24. Bxd7 Bxb2 25. Bb5 Nd5 26. Bd2 $11 {½-½ Polak,T (2508)-Simacek,P 
(2489) Brno 2009} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
