1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Bd3
O-O 9. Bg5 {This closely related to the previous system became popular a few
years later. With the knight pinned, the thematic ...b7-b5 remains possible,
but without ensuring the pawn retrieval by force. But developing the bishop so
early delays the king's evacuation from the center, offering Black an
additional tempo to organize his counterplay. Not last, the b2-pawn is hanging
in certain lines. It cost me a few painful losses until I found the right way
and move order to react.} Re8 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2 Nbd7 11. O-O a6 12. a4 {
transposes to a not too popular line of the Penrose attack (see line 13).})
10... c4 $1 {The key element in Black's counterplay.} 11. Bc2 (11. Bxc4 Nxe4 $1
$15 12. Bxd8 $2 Nxc3+) 11... b5 12. a3 {White needs slowing down the queenside
majority.} (12. O-O b4 13. Nb5 Ba6 14. Ba4 Rxe4 15. Qc2 Re7 16. Rfe1 Rb7 17.
Nbd4 Nbd7 $11 {Dessaules,P (2353)-Sikorsky,R (2400) ICCF email 2014 (½-½, 33)
} 18. Bc6 Rc8 19. Bxb7 Bxb7 $44 {Black will soon have two pawns for the
exchange, with a threatening queenside majority.}) 12... Bd7 $1 {Black should
not use half measures. He needs preparing ...a7-a5 and ...b5-b4 as soon as
possible, otherwise having concealed the control over the d4-square may leave
him slightly worse in an one-sided posiition.} (12... a5 {is a slightly less
accurate, though apparently viable, move order:} 13. Nxb5 $1 ({If} 13. O-O {
Black is not even forced to transpose below, as he could consider} Ba6 14. Re1
Nbd7 15. Nd4 Qb6 16. Nc6 Bb7 $15 {Erdos,V (2577)-Szuk,B (2416) Hungary 2009 
(½-½, 25)}) 13... Qb6 14. Qd4 Qxd4 (14... Qxb5 $2 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qxf6 Nd7
17. Qd4 c3 18. bxc3 Qb2 19. Kd2 Nc5 20. Qxc5 dxc5 21. Rhb1 {with a promising
ending in Chernin,A (2600)-Marin,M (2515) Budapest 1993 (1-0, 44)}) 15. Nfxd4
Nxe4 16. Be3 (16. Nc7 Nxg5+ 17. Nxe8 Bxd4 18. Nxd6 Ba6 19. f4 Bxb2 20. Ra2 Bc3+
21. Kd1 Nd7 22. fxg5 Nb6 $44) 16... Bxd4 17. Nxd4 (17. Nc7 Nxf2 $1 $19) 17...
Nf6 {Black will win a pawn but the e3-bishop is dangerous.}) (12... a6 13. O-O
Nbd7 {transposes to the kind of position I would prefer avoiding, as Black has
no real counterplay.}) 13. O-O a5 14. Nd4 {White has to react quickly before
Black gets playing ...Na6 and ...b5-b4.} ({Preparing e4-e5 with the queenside
unstable is simply bad.} 14. Re1 Na6 15. e5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 b4 17. axb4 axb4 18.
Nxd7 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Qxd7 20. Ne4 (20. Ba4 Qc8 21. Qe7 Nc5 22. Bxf6 bxc3 $17)
20... Nxd5 $17 {½-½ Istratescu,A (2575)-Florean,A (2455) Bucharest 1998}) (
14. Nd2 {is solid but not dangerous.} Na6 15. a4 {Chytilek,R (2393)-Kanovsky,D
(2462) Czechia 2011 (1-0, 33)} b4 16. Nb5 Rc8 17. Qe2 (17. Nxd6 Bg4 18. Qxg4
Qxd6 {With at last enough compensation. Black is well coordinated and White's
queenside offers him lots of worries. Besides, there is no quick way of
putting his extra pawn into motion.}) 17... h6 18. Bxf6 (18. Be3 c3 19. bxc3
bxc3 20. Nc4 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxb5 22. axb5 Rxe4 23. bxa6 Rexc4 $13) 18... Qxf6
19. Nxc4 Rxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 21. Qd3 Qxb2 22. Nxd6 Qxc2 23. Qxa6 Bxa1 24. Nxc8
Bxc8 25. Qxa5 Bd4 26. Qxb4 Qxe4 27. Qb8 Qc2 28. a5 Kg7 $13) 14... Qb6 15. Be3
Qb7 16. a4 $1 {This was my main move in the old analysis and the computers'
favorite nowadays. Most of my analysis got the engines' approval.} (16. Bf4 Na6
17. Qf3 (17. Bxd6 b4 $15) 17... b4 18. axb4 axb4 19. Nce2 b3 20. Bb1 {A
typical situation. The bishop has no mobility at all.} Nc5 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22.
Ng3 Nfxe4 23. Bxe4 Bxd4 24. Bxd6 Nxe4 25. Nxe4 Bf5 26. Nc3 Bd3 $19 {With a
decisive domination, Sakaev,K (2641)-Mueller,K (2500) Germany 2007 (0-1, 65).})
(16. Qf3 Na6 17. Bg5 (17. Rad1 b4 18. Nce2 Nc5 19. Ng3 {Polak,T (2526)
-Kanovsky,D (2472) Pardubice 2011 (½-½, 47)} h5 20. Bg5 Nh7 21. Bf4 Qb6 $17)
17... Ng4 (17... Nh5 $2 18. Nf5 $1 $16) 18. Nc6 (18. hxg4 Bxd4 $15 19. Bf6 $2
Bxg4 20. Qf4 Bxf6 21. Qxf6 Qb6 $17) 18... Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 (19... Rxe5 $5 {
is slightly more ambitious.} 20. Bf6 Nc5 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. Rfc1 b4 23. axb4
axb4 24. Nd1 Rxa1 25. Rxa1 b3 26. Bb1 Na4 $15 {with annoying queenside
pressure, leaving hite struggling despite his extra exchange. His queenside
pieces are simply frozen!}) 20. Bf6 b4 21. axb4 axb4 22. Nd1 Nc5 (22... Bb5 $1
$15) 23. Ne3 (23. Rxa8 Qxa8 24. Bxe5 dxe5 $5 $11 {Ziegler,A (2372)-Marin,M 
(2555) Gothenburg 2000 (½-½, 58)}) 23... Rxa1 24. Rxa1 b3 25. Bxe5 dxe5 26.
Nxc4 bxc2 27. Nd6 Qxb2 {0-1 Sachdev,T (2417)-Moradiabadi,E (2506) Reykjavik
2008 Probably the result in the database is wrong as the game should end in a
perpetual:} 28. Qxf7+ Kh8 29. Qf6+) 16... bxa4 $1 {Clearing space for the
pieces, depriving White of the b5-square and forcing him losing coordination
in order to retrieve the pawn.} 17. Qd2 (17. f3 Na6 18. Nxa4 $2 Nxd5 $17) 17...
Na6 18. f3 Nc5 19. Nxa4 {After general exchanges on a4, White would install
his knight to c6. But back in the '90s, I found a few tactical tricks without
the help of the (then still weak) computers.} Nb3 $1 20. Bxb3 (20. Nxb3 cxb3
21. Bd3 Nxd5 $1 22. exd5 Qb4 $17 {The simultaneous threats ...Rxe3 and ...Bxa4
retrieve the piece with interest.}) 20... cxb3 21. Rfc1 {Hoping for Nc6.} ({
After} 21. Ra3 Nxd5 22. exd5 Qb4 $15 {The a3-rook is hanging in some lines,
too.}) (21. Bf2 Rec8 22. Qd3 Qb4 (22... Rab8 $15) 23. Be1 Qb8 24. Kh2 Nh5 25.
Bd2 Qa7 26. Be3 Qa6 $15 {Psakhis,L-Marin,M World Chess Network (rapid) 2003 
(1-0, 67)}) 21... Nxd5 $3 {Once again this trick.} 22. exd5 Rxe3 ({My initial
analysis went} 22... Qb4 {but I overlooked a key move in the following line:}
23. Nc6 Bxc6 24. Qxb4 axb4 25. dxc6 Rxe3 26. Kf1 $3 {It is essential not only
to evacuate the king from the dangerous diagonal but also to prevent ...Re2.} (
26. Kh1 Re2 27. Nb6 Rxa1 28. Rxa1 Rxb2 $19 29. c7 Rc2 30. Ra8+ Bf8 31. c8=Q
Rxc8 32. Nxc8 b2) (26. c7 Ree8 $15) 26... Ree8 27. Nb6 Ra2 28. c7 Bxb2 29. c8=Q
Rxc8 30. Rxc8+ Kg7 {True, this offers reasonable drawing chances, but the main
line is just double-edged, deserving being preferred.} 31. Rd1 (31. Rb1 Bd4 32.
Rxb3 Bxb6 33. Rxb4 Bc5 34. Rb7 Rf2+ 35. Ke1 Rxg2 36. Rcc7 Kf6 37. Rxf7+ Ke5 38.
Rxh7 Kf4 39. Rb3 Rg1+ 40. Ke2 Rg2+ 41. Kd3 Kxf3 {Again with reasonable saving
chances.}) 31... Bc3 32. Nc4 b2 33. Rd8 Ra1 34. Nxb2 Bxb2 35. Rxa1 Bxa1 36.
Rxd6 Bc3 37. Rb6 h5 {Due to the b-pawn Black should probably hold this ending.}
) 23. Qxe3 Qb4 24. Rd1 (24. Ne6 Bxe6 25. Kh1 Bd7 $17) 24... Bxa4 25. Qd2 Qc4
$44 {A pawn, an active bishops pair and White's instability in the center
offer Black good compensation.} *

